##Who will be the first to go down when the outbreak hits the airline industry?

Weixin Signal Wowjiemian

Function introduction, the interface news is China has the influence original financial and economic new media, only serves the independent thinking crowd

Reporter: Chen Xiaoshuang, editor Tang Jun: Shen Xiaoge

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)


The plane was parked on the tarmac in the Sun, and you could hear the money melting.





The plane was parked on the tarmac in the Sun, and you could hear the money melting.



Planes are grounded, flights are canceled, occupancy continues to drop... The impact on the airline industry has been most immediate.

Not long ago, China Southern, one of the country's three major airlines, held an internal meeting, proposed operating extremely difficult, chairman Wang Changshun bluntly to live tight. Nearly 30 of China Southern's widebody jets, including five Airbus A380s, have been grounded in Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport for nearly a month, and many of its widebody captains have not flown in a month.

Airlines around the world, not just China Southern, are preparing for the worst.

If this state of affairs continues for another month or two, airlines that already have "basic diseases" may be the first to fall.

###Bad Operating Data

Frequent Flyer program data showed that, affected by the epidemic, the number of passenger traffic by civil aviation in February was 8.34 million, down 84.5 percent year-on-year, and the passenger occupancy rate remained at a relatively low level of 40 percent to 50 percent. So far this year, the minimum daily number of aircraft movements at the mainland's airports is only 5,380. That compares with an average of 36,000 flights a day before the outbreak, a precipitous drop back to 2001 levels.

5,380 flights a day, which means up to 2,690 aircraft take off and land, while the current total of nearly 4,000 civil aviation passenger aircraft in China, more than 1,000 aircraft have to face the embarrassing situation of parking.

This is the winter of Chinese civil aviation industry without a doubt. Recently, the Civil Aviation Administration announced 16 policy measures to promote the steady development of the industry, which proposes to extend the implementation of the 2019 Winter Air flight schedule to May 2. According to previous plans, Beijing Daxing International Airport would have welcomed the first busy summer and autumn season on March 29, and many airlines such as China Eastern Airlines and China Southern Airlines would have transferred more routes to Daxing International Airport.

"You can hear the money melting as the plane sits in the sun on the tarmac, " says the industry analogy, which vividly describes the loss to the airline from the parking lot and the direct loss from not flying.

The fixed cost of operation mainly includes aircraft depreciation, management expenses, financial expenses and so on. These expenses are relatively stable and can be directly converted into daily average fixed cost according to historical data. According to the statistics of the big blue hole of civil aviation, the fixed cost of Air China group is about 101 million yuan per day; that of China Southern Group is about 135 million yuan per day; and that of China Eastern Group is about 83 million yuan per day.

Another problem with the large number of flights is that cash is not collected, exacerbating the cash flow crunch. Cash is the lifeblood of a normal airline operation, says Roland Berger, noting that airlines'ability to liquidate their operations is limited by the high capital investment and tariff control brought about by the earlier purchase of aircraft, and under the impact of emergencies, air passenger flow is hit by tremendous impact, operating cash inflow will be more limited.

Airlines'cash flow has been under unprecedented pressure as capacity and revenue have been slashed, and as a result of previous free refund policies, there has been heavy demand for refunds. As of March 2,24.545 million tickets had been refunded by domestic and foreign airlines, involving a total face value of 27.1 billion yuan, according to data released by the China Air Transport Association.

Some of the cash-strapped airlines, the impact of the epidemic has led to worse liquidity.

China Southern had only 1.193 billion yuan in cash on its books as of September 30,2019, the lowest amount since the airline went public, according to the three major airlines'third quarter results last year. Air China's currency was 8.253 billion yuan and China Eastern's was 1.549 billion yuan at the end of the reporting period. In addition, the private airline Chunqiu Airlines had 8.235 billion yuan, while Jixiang Airlines had 2.786 billion yuan.

Before this cash flow originally appears the problem hna normal operation is affected, repeatedly delays the passenger free refund matter. HNA and its Tianjin Airlines, capital airlines, Western Airlines, Jinpeng Airlines, Urumqi Air, etc. were affected by the backlog of centralized refund, refund cycle has been extended. HNA has even offered passengers a 1:1.1 voucher payment option that converts ticket payments into airline vouchers for future use. The untenable hna finally announced that a working group led by the Hainan Provincial Government to resolve the group's financial difficulties had been set up to assist and fully advance the group's risk management work.

But if the option to continue flying, but also involves fuel, landing fees, crew salaries and catering costs, the occupancy rate can not keep up, or loss.

The cost of flights from Shenzhen to Chengdu on March 2 was calculated by the aviation media. It was found that due to the low ticket price and the low occupancy rate, the airline lost money on the whole flight. The lowest fare from Shenzhen to Chengdu on that day was 50 yuan, with 66 passengers, he outlined the cost of fuel consumption, parking fees, bridge fees, electricity, passenger service fees, security checks, crew and ground personnel salaries, landing fees, depreciation fees, maintenance fees, and so on, and assuming that the flight can have a certain amount of cargo revenue, found that this flight to more than 80,000 losses.

Qiu Lianzhong, a visiting professor at the China Civil Aviation Administration Cadre College, wrote that "at a time when price elasticity is almost zero, trying to reduce prices to promote sales is even more suicidal. "

Civil aviation lost 24.59 billion yuan in February, of which 20.96 billion yuan was lost by airlines, according to the CAAC.

"If the epidemic continues to affect 1-2 months, China may have the collapse of airlines. " Civil Aviation expert Lin Zhijie on the interface of News Analysis: Not that big companies are easy to live, small companies will not survive; But the original profit airline may be able to endure a boil, there are a lot of "basic disease" is easy to turn critical illness.

Lin Zhijie believes that the pressure to meet the following five symptoms is relatively high: losing money year after year, with little savings; having a high ratio of assets and liabilities, and having to pay a lot of money every month; renting more planes and paying a lot of rent every month; and having a low proportion of airline subsidies, the main source of income comes from selling tickets to tourists; privately owned, bank loans are relatively hard to come by.

In addition, in the long run, the epidemic will also affect the training of working pilots. A China Southern Airlines captain told interface news that serving pilots need regular training in simulators in order to obtain flight qualifications. Since there are no simulators of some types of aircraft in China, travel is restricted during the epidemic, it is likely that some pilots will not be able to complete their regular training, which will result in a lack of flight qualification at a later stage, leaving the aircraft unmanned after the end of the outbreak.

###Airlines save themselves

In order to relieve the pressure of cash flow, the most direct way is to increase the capital reserve.

After the outbreak, a number of airlines issued ultra-short-term financing vouchers. February 10, Shenzhen Airlines, Xiamen Airlines on the same day issued epidemic prevention and control debt, a total of 1.2 billion yuan. On February 17, Sichuan Airlines also issued 710 million yuan in epidemic prevention and control debt to supplement the company's working capital, this includes liquidity requirements such as fuel costs for the company's Day to day operations, consumables and spare parts purchases, as well as additional liquidity related to the fight against COVID-19. China Eastern, China Southern and others have also issued more than ten billion ultra short term bonds.

In addition, during the epidemic, Airlines also through for the government, business charter business model to generate revenue. In mid-to-late February, there was a large number of demand for returning workers to work to travel. In response to this market situation, a number of domestic airlines, including China Southern Airlines, China Eastern Airlines, Xiamen Airlines, Shanhang Airlines and Chunqiu Airlines, have launched government-enterprise charter services, which can not only increase the speed of returning to work for the enterprises, is also the civil aviation industry in the cold period of rare airline business.

However, some industry insiders admitted that the charter flight is a product of special circumstances, on the enterprise's customer organization has high requirements, for cash flow is a drop in the bucket. All of HNA's 11 airlines offer charter flights for government and corporate customers, but as of March 5, only 36 flights had been chartered.

In order to be able to as many flights as possible and not to lose money on the balance between the airlines have done a lot of internal analysis and accurate trade-off.

An employee in the marketing department of a southwest regional airline revealed to the interface news that his current job is to conduct route evaluation, "In the year of the Olympics, a lot of airlines are increasing the number of flights to Japan, and the outbreak adds a lot of uncertainty to the scheduling of subsequent routes. We've cancelled a lot of loss-making routes, and we've temporarily cancelled about 60-70% of our routes. At the same time, we need to restructure the airline network and evaluate all the routes that can be flown."

In order to stimulate the aviation market demand and return the funds, Cathay Pacific has introduced an unlimited free change of ticket policy and early bird discount. Customers who purchased tickets from March 9 to April 20 do not need to pay the change of ticket fee, the same booking can be rescheduled to any travel 2021 prior to 28 February.

Reducing cost by reducing salary is one of the possible choices for enterprises. According to the reporter, HNA has taken unpaid leave rotation system. Other Airlines, because pilots, flight attendants and other front-line staff part of the income by flying hours, not only fly minimum wage, so in the income is also affected.

In addition to the airlines to help themselves, the authorities have also introduced a number of measures to support the recovery of the aviation industry. The Civil Aviation Administration actively promoted the reduction of fees and burdens by reducing the standard take-off and landing fees of first-and second-class airports by 10 per cent and waiving parking fees, and reducing the standard air route fees (except overflight) by 10 per cent. Domestic Airlines domestic flights aviation fuel import and export price differential reduced by 8% . The central government will provide financial support to Chinese and foreign airlines operating international scheduled passenger flights.

According to Fei Changzhun's statistics, according to the above-mentioned reward standard, between January 23 and March 3, china Southern Airlines, Air China, China Eastern Airlines and Hainan Airlines will receive 177 million yuan, 168 million yuan, 127 million yuan and 50 million yuan respectively.

###As the epidemic spreads around the world, which one will be the first to go?

As the outbreak stabilized, domestic flights resumed. Among them, HNA has resumed more than 3,700 flights since March. China Eastern resumed 1,050 flights by the end of February, mainly covering rework routes from Yunnan, Sichuan and Shaanxi to Shanghai, Zhejiang, Jiangsu and Guangdong. According to the study, China Eastern Airlines resumed more than 2,700 classes before March 28, is expected to carry out around 1,300 classes a day, accounting for 50% of the original plan.

Cardi, a real-time indicator of the impact of the new crown disease on airline operations, showed that the impact on domestic routes began to diminish at the end of February, according to Fiyo.

However, due to the spread of the epidemic in the global scope, international routes and Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan routes still have no improvement, the current decline is still around 70% of the trough.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 21st the International Air Transport Association (IATA) released a preliminary assessment of the new pneumonia outbreak, which will cost the global airline industry $29.3 billion and reduce passenger demand by 4.7% .

Less than half a month later, IATA sharply revised up its forecast, predicting a loss of between $63 billion and $113 billion in global air passenger traffic in 2020, depending on the extent of the epidemic.

In the wake of the outbreak, the number of expected travelers hitting the market has plummeted: 23 percent in China, 12 percent in Japan, 10 percent in Singapore, 14 percent in South Korea, 24 percent in Italy, 10 percent in France, 10 percent in Germany and 16 percent in Iran.

In addition, demand is expected to fall 11 per cent in Asia, excluding China, Japan, Singapore and South Korea. Demand will fall 7 per cent in Europe (excluding Italy, France and Germany) and 7 per cent in the Middle East (excluding Iran) .

At present, some foreign airlines have suffered heavy losses. Among them, Korean Air has suspended 89 routes, international capacity has dropped more than 80% , the fleet of 145 aircraft parking 100. Korean Air President Oh ki-hong said this is the most difficult time in the company's history, there is no way to predict how long this situation will continue, the company may face a crisis of survival.

The outbreak was the last straw that killed the troubled airlines.

The UK's largest regional airline, Flybe, which operates 40% of its flights in the UK and employs more than 2,000 people, has been in receivership for more than 40 years, the company announced on March 5 local time. Before the virus broke out, Flybe was already experiencing significant operational difficulties, with only three years of profitability since 2010. The British government had promised to provide # 100m in crucial loans. But a slump in travel demand hit by the new coronavirus has accelerated Flybe's woes, with bookings falling by nearly 50% in a week.

In response to the huge impact of the epidemic, airlines are preparing for the worst in terms of revenue. United Airlines, the most liquid of American Airlines, currently holds $5 billion worth of cash and short term investments, but despite that, united's worst case scenario for the future is a 70% decline in revenue in April 2020 and May 2020, a 60% decline in revenue in June 2020, a 40% decline in revenue in July 2020, and a 30% decline in revenue in August 2020, September 2020 and October 2020.

Seventeen years ago, when SARS broke out in 2003, passenger demand began to drop sharply in April. By the end of June, when the crisis was over, domestic passenger traffic by civil aviation had dropped by 19 percent and the daily utilization of aircraft had decreased by 1.9 hours, equivalent to one-fifth of the aircraft parking lots in the industry. The industry lost 2.8 billion yuan in 2008 and 1998, the two economic crisis outside the industry's largest overall loss.

But after the epidemic ended, the passenger traffic rose sharply, the second half of the passenger traffic and freight transport volume increased by 20.1% and 14.3% respectively. The rise in demand has also created a miracle: In the second quarter of the decline of 50% , China's civil aviation industry in 2003 actually achieved positive growth.

"during the SARS epidemic, I flew only one Boeing 737 a month and played basketball every day, " the Southern Airlines captain told interface news reporters. "But by July, my work situation was completely saturated and every flight was full. "

However, the new outbreak is likely to end without a pattern similar to that seen in 2003. On the one hand, the civil aviation industry has entered a medium-speed development stage since 2019, passenger traffic growth in 2019 is 7.9% , if normal operation is maintained, the growth rate is expected to be only around 7% in 2020.

On the other hand, the personal travel willingness reduces, the recovery still waits for a long time. According to the COVID-19 passenger demand and willingness to spend report released by Capse, a civil aviation service evaluation agency, 68 percent of passengers will travel less abroad in 2020 due to the outbreak.
